<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06275116 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06275116 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; GAME; RESULT; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Boston Red Sox wasted a 6-0 lead Monday, then came back as Jack Clark'stwo-run homer and Tom Brunansky's RBI double sparked a seventh-inning rallyand a 9-8 victory over the host Milwaukee Brewers.;   The Red Sox, who ended afour-game losing streak, closed to within 3 1/2 games of American LeagueEast-leading Toronto, which lost to California 2-1.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  RED SOX RALLY, MOVE WITHIN 3 1/2  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  A.L. ROUNDUP; BLUE JAYS' MAGIC NUMBER: 3; The magic number is the combinationof Blue Jays wins and Red Sox losses that will give the Blue Jays the A.L.East title.  </MEMO><TEXT>     The Red Sox led 6-0 after two innings, but Milwaukee scored four runs inthe third and Greg Vaughn hit a three-run homer in the fifth.; OTHER GAMES:Dave Winfield hit a two-run double in the eighth as the California Angels won2-1 in Toronto. A crowd of 50,321 raised Toronto's season attendance to3,900,880, a major league record. . . . Nolan Ryan reached the 5,500-strikeoutmark as the Seattle Mariners beat the Texas Rangers 3-2 in 11 innings inArlington, Texas. The Rangers won the second game of the doubleheader 2-0.Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. became the youngest player with 100 RBIs sinceDetroit's Al Kaline in 1956. Griffey is 21 years, 10 months; Kaline was 21years, 9 months. . . . Randy Bush, Pedro Munoz and Paul Sorrento homered asthe Minnesota Twins won 8-3 in Chicago. . . . Scott Sanderson got his 16th winbut was forced from the game when a line drive dislocated a finger as the NewYork Yankees won 3-0 in Cleveland. . . . Pete Incaviglia, Mickey Tettleton andLou Whitaker homered as the host Detroit Tigers beat the Baltimore Orioles 8-3.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury Ne